This is a simulation of a finite state Markov chain.

N <- 1000
j0 = 1
states <- c(j0,rep(NA,N))

for (j in 1:N){
  states[j+1] <- sample(3,1,prob = PJ[states[j],])

Roulette Simulation

  • Bet $1, always on RED. Play until the money is gone.
  1. How many games do we expect to play?
p = 18/38   # probability of winning
X0 = 100    # initial amount
N = 2500    # maximal number of spins

myCash = c(X0, rep(0,N)) # vector for my cash

spins <- rbinom(N,1,p) # simulate  N  spins ,from a bernoulli distribution-->0 or 1;loose or win

counter  = 1

while(myCash[counter] > 0 & counter <= N){ #this goes on until I loose all my money and reaches the maximal number of spins
  myCash[counter + 1] <- myCash[counter] + 2*spins[counter] -1
  counter <- counter + 1
}

plot(myCash, type = 'l',xlab = "Games")            # plot of my cash
abline(a = X0, b = -1/19, col = 2)  # plot expected trend

  1. What is the expected time until we go bankrupt?

Make 1000 simulations and record the time when the money runs out in each case.

N = 2500
times = rep(0,1000)

# simulate repeating 1000 experiments

for (j in 1:1000){
  
  myCash = c(X0, rep(0,N)) # vector for my cash
spins <- rbinom(N,1,p) # simulate N spins-->bernoulli 1 or 0
counter  = 1  

while(myCash[counter] > 0 & counter <= N){
  
  myCash[counter + 1] <- myCash[counter] + 2*spins[counter] -1
  counter <- counter + 1
}

# when j=1 the whole experiment runs and will record  the counter where it hit 0.
# counter is index on mycash

times[j] <- counter #this would be the time that I loose all my money 
}

paste("Mean time = ",round(mean(times),0))
## [1] "Mean time =  1772"

St.Â Petersburg System

  • Starting bet $1, always on RED. Double after each loss if possible.
  • Play until the money is gone.
  • Repeat this a number of times.
set.seed(124)
p = 18/38   # probability of winning
X0 = 100    # initial amount
N = 500    # maximal number of spins

myCash = c(X0, rep(0,N)) # vector for my cash

spins <- rbinom(N,1,p) # simulate  N  spins

counter  = 1  # keep track of number of games

lastspin = 1  # initialize memory of last games

myBet = 1

while(myCash[counter] > 0 & counter <= N){
  #this goes on until I loose all my money or reaches the maximal number of spins
  
  myBet <- min(c(2*myBet,myCash[counter])) #bet is double down if loose
  
  if(lastspin == 1){myBet <- 1} #if win bet is $1
  
  myCash[counter + 1] <- myCash[counter] + (2*spins[counter] - 1)*myBet
  lastspin <- spins[counter]
  counter <- counter + 1
}

plot(myCash, type = 'l')            # plot of my cash
abline(a = X0, b = -1/19, col = 2)  # plot expected trend

What is happening? Tell the story. Then try again.

Redo with house limit (maximal bet).

set.seed(128)
p = 18/38   # probability of winning
maxBet = 20     # maximal bet
X0 = 100    # initial amount
N = 300    # maximal number of spins
myCash = c(X0, rep(0,N)) # vector for my cash

spins <- rbinom(N,1,p) # simulate  N  spins
counter  = 1  # keep track of number of games
lastspin = 1  # initialize memory of last games
myBet = 1

while(myCash[counter] > 0 & counter <= N){
  myBet <- min(c(2*myBet,myCash[counter], maxBet)) #now its either the doubled bet, last amount left with me or the maximal bet
  
  if(lastspin == 1){myBet <- 1}
  myCash[counter + 1] <- myCash[counter] + (2*spins[counter] - 1)*myBet
  lastspin <- spins[counter]
  counter <- counter + 1
}
plot(myCash, type = 'l')            # plot of my cash
abline(a = X0, b = -1/19, col = 2)  # plot expected trend

Hard to do this by looking at the maze. Compute with a suitable power of the transition matrix.

## [1] 0.1461227
  1. What is the probability that he is in room 9 after 30 steps?
# function to compute matrix powers
powerP = function(A,n){
  B <- 0*A
  diag(B) <- 1  # make identity matrix
  #now B is the identity matrix, it is for initial multiplication
  #if you multiply a matrix with the identity matrix, it is the same
  
  for (j in 1:n){
    B <- B%*%A
    }
  return(B)
} 
powerP(P,30)[1,9] #P^30
## [1] 0.219303

#1000 simulations

steps=30
last_step =c()
simulation_number = 10000

for (i in 1:simulation_number){
  
  states = rep(1,steps + 1)
  
  for (j in 1:steps){
    states[j+1] <- sample(9,1,prob = P[states[j],])
  }
  
  last_step[i] = states[steps+1] #last room he ends up on each iteration
}

table(last_step)
## last_step
##    1    2    3    4    5    6    7    8    9 
##  884 1461  988 1178 1386 1052  560  286 2205
